# Order of Elites — Architecture Review

## What You Have (The Big Picture)

```
Browser (React :3000)
    │
    ├──── REST calls (axios) ────────► Django DRF (:8000)
    │                                       │
    └──── WebSocket (socket.io) ────► Node/Express (:4000)
                                            │
                                    calls Django API to auth sockets
                                            │
                                ┌──────────┴──────────┐
                                ▼                     ▼
                           PostgreSQL             Redis (cache +
                           (:5432)                sessions)
                                │
                           pgAdmin (:5050)

Production: Nginx reverse-proxies everything → serves React build
```

All services live in Docker containers on a shared `ooe_network`.

---

## Verdict on the Stack: **Keep It, With Targeted Fixes**

**React + Django REST + Node/Socket.IO + PostgreSQL + Redis + Docker + Nginx** is actually a well-reasoned choice for this project. Here's why:

| Concern | Assessment |
|---|---|
| Is React overkill? | No — a game dashboard with real-time updates, many dynamic UI components, and planned monetization *needs* a reactive frontend. |
| Is Django the right backend? | Yes — DRF is battle-tested for REST APIs, Django's ORM + migrations are perfect for a complex relational model (30 ranks, missions, syndicates, etc.), and built-in auth/token management saves time. |
| Should Node exist separately? | **Yes, this is the right call.** Real-time chat over WebSockets (socket.io) would be awkward in Django (you'd need Django Channels + ASGI). Keeping it separate is clean. |
| Is PostgreSQL right? | Yes — the game has a very relational data model (users, cities, syndicates, missions, items, chat rooms). Postgres is the right DB. |
| Is Redis needed? | Yes — cooldown timers, session storage, and cache are all natural Redis use-cases here. |
| Is Docker the right deployment? | Yes — multi-service project, real domain, SSL. Docker Compose is appropriate. |

**You're on the right path. This stack is solid.**

